Henry
to
the
door.
Without
hesitation
I
said,
'Go
where
you
will,
my
boy;
but,
till
I
call
you,
return
not
here.'
"Henry,
I
could
see,
did
not
like
his
dismissal.
That
boy
is
young,
but
a
thinker;
his
meditative
eye
shines
on
me
strangely
sometimes.
He
half
feels
what
links
me
to
Shirley;
he
half
guesses
that
there
is
a
dearer
delight
in
the
reserve
with
which
I
am
treated
than
in
all
the
endearments
he
is
allowed.
The
young,
lame,
half
grown
lion
would
growl
at
me
now
and
then,
because
I
have
tamed
his
lioness
and
am
her
keeper,
did
not
the
habit
of
discipline
and
the
